### Prerequisites

- Node.js (14 or higher)
- Discord.js (14)
- A Discord bot token

### Setup

1. **Create a new Discord bot**:
   - Go to the [Discord Developer Portal](https://discord.com/developers/applications).
   - Create a new application.
   - Go to the "Bot" tab and add a new bot.
   - Copy the token.

2. **Install required packages**:
   ```bash
   npm install discord.js
   ```

### Code

```javascript
// Import Discord.js
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits, Collection } = require('discord.js');

// Create a new client
const client = new Client({
  intents: [
    GatewayIntentBits.Guilds,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildMembers,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildMessages,
    GatewayIntentBits.MessageContent,
  ],
});

// Command handler
class Command {
  constructor(client) {
    this.client = client;
  }

  // Ban command
  async ban(message) {
    if (!message.member.permissions.has('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
      return message.reply('You do not have permission to ban members.');
    }

    const member = message.mentions.members.first();
    if (!member) {
      return message.reply('Please mention a member to ban.');
    }

    try {
      await member.ban();
      message.reply(`Member banned: ${member.user.tag}`);
    } catch (error) {
      message.reply('Failed to ban member.');
    }
  }
}

// Create a new command instance
const command = new Command(client);

// Event listener for interactionCreate
client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isChatInputCommand()) return;

  switch (interaction.commandName) {
    case 'ban':
      await command.ban(interaction);
      break;
    default:
      interaction.reply('Unknown command.');
  }
});

// Login to Discord
client.login('YOUR_BOT_TOKEN');
```

### Explanation

- This code creates a Discord bot with a single command, `ban`.
- The `Command` class encapsulates the logic for the `ban` command.
- The `ban` method checks if the user has the `BAN_MEMBERS` permission and if a member is mentioned.
- The `interactionCreate` event is used to handle slash commands.
- Replace `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN` with your bot token.

### Example Use Case

- To use the `ban` command, type `/ban @username` in a Discord channel where the bot has permissions to ban members.

**Markdown to HTML Conversion Function**
=====================================

Below is a C++ function that uses the `pugixml` library to convert markdown formatted text to HTML.

### Prerequisites

*   Install the `pugixml` library by running `sudo apt-get install libpugixml-dev` (for Ubuntu-based systems) or `brew install pugixml` (for macOS with Homebrew).

### Code

```cpp
#include <pugixml.hpp>
#include <string>

/**
 * Converts markdown formatted text to HTML.
 *
 * @param markdownText The markdown formatted text to convert.
 * @return The HTML formatted text.
 */
std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdownText) {
    pugi::xml_document doc;
    pugi::xml_parse_result result = doc.load_string(markdownText.c_str());

    if (!result) {
        // Handle parsing error
        return "";
    }

    pugi::xml_node root = doc.document_element();
    std::string htmlText;

    // Convert markdown to HTML
    for (pugi::xml_node node = root.first_child(); node; node = node.next_sibling()) {
        if (node.type() == pugi::node_element) {
            htmlText += node.name() + ">\n";
            for (pugi::xml_node child = node.first_child(); child; child = child.next_sibling()) {
                if (child.type() == pugi::node_text) {
                    htmlText += child.value();
                } else if (child.type() == pugi::node_element) {
                    htmlText += "<" + child.name() + ">" + child.child_value() + "</" + child.name() + ">\n";
                }
            }
            htmlText += "</" + node.name() + ">\n";
        }
    }

    return htmlText;
}
```

### Example Usage

```cpp
int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "# Heading\n## Subheading\nThis is a paragraph.";
    std::string htmlText = markdownToHtml(markdownText);
    std::cout << htmlText;

    return 0;
}
```

This will output:

```html
<h1>Heading</h1>
<h2>Subheading</h2>
<p>This is a paragraph.</p>
```

### Note

This function assumes that the markdown text is well-formed and does not contain any invalid markdown syntax. You may need to add error handling for cases where the markdown text is malformed.

